data.name: IfcOptionFederatedExportTooltip
data.value:
Export all models to a single IFC file. If you clear the checkbox, each model will be exported to a separate IFC file.
This option is available only if you export all models in a single thread (when the "Run in parallel threads" checkbox is cleared).

data.name: IfcOptionParallelTooltip
data.value:
Export each model in a separate thread. This speeds up the export but requires more RAM.
This option is available only when you export each model to a separate IFC file (when the "Federated export" checkbox is cleared).

data.name: IfcOptionExportGuidsTooltip
data.value:
Export GUIDs of Revizto objects to IFC GUIDs. For each object, Revizto will look for its GUID in the following properties: 1. Revizto / Ifc Guid 2. Item / GUID 3. IFC / GLOBALID
The first GUID that is found will be exported to an IFC GUID.
If you clear the checkbox, Revizto will generate random IFC GUIDs.

data.name: IfcOptionHierarchyTooltip
data.value:
Export the entire model hierarchy.
If you clear the checkbox, only geometries and composite objects will be exported. This is how export to IFC was performed in Revizto versions 5.9 and earlier.

data.name: IfcOptionRefElevationTooltip
data.value:
Export the height of Revizto objects to RefElevation property of IfcSite objects. Use this option if you want to view the resulting files in an authoring tool that requires filling RefElevation.
If you clear the checkbox, the RefElevation property will be blank.

data.name: IfcOptionLocalPlacementTooltip
data.value:
Export the height of Revizto objects to the Z-value of the LocalPlacement property of IfcSite objects.
If you clear the checkbox, the Z-value of the LocalPlacement property will be blank. Use this option if you want to view the resulting files in Autodesk Revit and you selected the "Export height to RefElevation" checkbox.

data.name: IfcOptionSwapLocalPlacements
data.value: Swap local placements of IfcSite and IfcBuilding

data.name: IfcOptionSwapLocalPlacementsTooltip
data.value: Swap local placement coordinates of IfcSite and IfcBuilding. This is required for correct import of the resulting IFC files to Revit 2022 or earlier.

data.name: IfcOptionAssignTypesTooltip
data.value:
If you clear the checkbox, all objects will have the default types: IfcBuildingElementProxy for leaf objects and IfcBuildingElementPart for branch objects.
If you clear the checkbox, all objects will have the default types: IfcBuildingElementProxy for leaf objects and IfcBuildingElementPart for branch objects.

data.name: RvtDoublePropsCompatibilityFormat_Tooltip
data.value:
<Bold>Warning: Changing this option mid-project is not recommended!</Bold>
If you select this checkbox, object properties will be exported in the same format as in Revizto 5.12 and earlier versions. Some of the numeric object properties might be exported as text, which can cause issues with "<" and ">" comparison operators in search sets. This option is recommended for projects created in Revizto 5.12 or earlier.
If you clear this checkbox, numeric properties will be exported as numbers, resolving the issue with comparison operators in search sets. This option is recommended for projects created in Revizto 5.13 or later.
If you change this option mid-project, ensure that the search sets, favorite properties, and property conditions in appearance templates and clash grouping rules provide correct results. They might need to be recreated.
